goals.question: What is the average obesity rate across all states?
goals.visualization: bar chart of average obesity rate per state
goals.rationale: This visualization will give an overview of the obesity rates across all states and help identify states with higher or lower rates.

goals.question: What is the distribution of obesity rates across all states?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help identify the range of obesity rates across all states and the frequency of occurrence of each rate.

goals.question: Which state has the highest obesity rate?
goals.visualization: choropleth map of obesity rates by state
goals.rationale: This visualization will help identify the state with the highest obesity rate and provide a geographical context for the data.

goals.question: Is there a correlation between obesity rates and state population?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of obesity rates vs state population
goals.rationale: This visualization will help identify any patterns or trends between obesity rates and state population, and whether there is a positive or negative correlation.

goals.question: How does the obesity rate vary by region?
goals.visualization: box plot of obesity rates by region
goals.rationale: This visualization will help identify any regional differences in obesity rates and provide insights into potential factors that may contribute to the differences.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.sort_values(by='rate', ascending=False)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
    plt.bar(data['state'], data['rate'], color='c')
    plt.axhline(data['rate'].mean(), color='r', linestyle='--', label=f"Average: {data['rate'].mean():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('State')
    plt.ylabel('Obesity Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the average obesity rate across all states?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['rate'], bins=10, color='blue', alpha=0.7, edgecolor='black')
    plt.axvline(data['rate'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2, label=f"Median: {data['rate'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Obesity Rate')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of obesity rates across all states?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Load US states shapefile
    us_states = gpd.read_file("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/PublicaMundi/MappingAPI/master/data/geojson/us-states.geojson")

    # Merge data with shapefile
    merged_data = us_states.set_index("postal").join(data.set_index("state"))

    # Create choropleth map
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(12, 6))
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
    cax = divider.append_axes("right", size="5%", pad=0.1)
    merged_data.plot(column="rate", cmap="coolwarm", linewidth=0.8, ax=ax, edgecolor="0.8", legend=True, cax=cax)

    # Add title
    plt.title("Which state has the highest obesity rate?", wrap=True)

    # Add line for the state with the highest obesity rate
    max_rate = data["rate"].max()
    max_state = data.loc[data["rate"] == max_rate, "state"].values[0]
    max_state_geometry = merged_data.loc[max_state, "geometry"]
    max_state_boundary = max_state_geometry.boundary
    ax.plot(max_state_boundary, color="black", linewidth=2, label=f"{max_state}: {max_rate:.2f}")

    # Add legend
    ax.legend()

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # There is no state population data in the dataset, so we cannot create a scatter plot of obesity rates vs state population
    # Instead, we can create a bar chart of obesity rates by state
    data = data.sort_values(by='rate', ascending=False)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
    plt.bar(data['state'], data['rate'], color='blue')
    plt.xlabel('State')
    plt.ylabel('Obesity Rate')
    plt.title('Obesity Rates by State', wrap=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
